Data exploration and commentary

Paul Hively

March 29, 2016

Problem statement

My goal is to find a way to accurately forecast fundraising revenue.

The existing model has two components. First, the probability a solicitation \(S_{i}\) comes in before the end of the fiscal year is a function of the current stage progress \(c\) and time until the end of the year \(t\), \(P(S_{i}=1)=f(c_{i},t)\). The expected FRP in the current fiscal year is this probability times the expected amount, \(E(FRP)=P(S_{i}=1)E(S_{i})\).

For the probability model, I assume that there should also be some effect due to the average close rate, season (e.g.people give more in December), planned ask amount, actual ask amount, and potentially interactions. Something like this:

\[P(S_{ij}=1)=f(c_{i},t,\mu,t_{i}^{*},a_{j}^{*},a_{j})\]

It makes sense to start with a few straightforward classifiers, but Id also like to look into nesting models.

Visualizations

The dataset includes all closed (successful or unsuccessful) solicitations with an add date on or after 7/1/2011. Data is obtained from the first tab of the Booth solicitation history report (saved as a .csv).

source("Rscript0 - libraries.R")
#### Run Rscript1 to load data ----
source("Rscript1 - data load and transform.R")

Begin with some visualizations of time in each stage:

Theres extremely obvious bimodality in most cases. Note in particular that while PG is skewed positive overall, there seem to be two groups: takes a while and takes a long while. The purple Days from ask to actual is about as perfect a mixture of two \(N(\mu_{k},\sigma^{2}_{k})\) as Ive ever seen. Might be interesting to see if a certain population just takes longer.

There isnt much data in the oral pledge stage so things are a bit bumpier here.

Booked indicates whether the solicitation came in at \(>\)$0, and FY.plan, FY.clear, FY.ask, FY.oral indicate whether the solicitation closed in the same fiscal year as that stage was reached. Combinations of these five indicators will be the dependent variables. plan2actual, clear2actual, ask2actual, oral2actual are measured in days. The other covariates should be self-explanatory.

Peak ask occurs around Nov-Dec and Mar each year. Not nearly as much oral pledge data; usually oral to booked is fast enough that the date isnt captured in the system. (The current model rolls ask and oral together.)

Finally, lets take a look at the booked versus declined solicitations by stage by fiscal year closed.

Confidence bands are based on the variance for a binomial random variable, \(\sqrt{\frac{p(1-p)}{n}}\) (assuming independence).

This is fascinating; a solicitation entering plan or clear in December or plan in April-May is more likely to be refused rather than booked. Is there a specific year driving that?

2010, 2016, 2017 dont have enough data so theyre dropped. 2011 didnt have much stage progress in the second half of the year.

Looks like 2012 was a good year; other than that its normal to have lots of duds in those winter months

Discrete covariates

Im thinking time to close is not the natural outcome measure; a model predicting time to close cant be swapped out directly with the existing one. Recall from above:

For the probability model, I assume that there should also be some effect due to the average close rate, season (e.g.people give more in December), planned ask amount, actual ask amount, and potentially interactions. Something like this:

\[P(S_{ij}=1)=f(c_{i},t,\mu,t_{i}^{*},a_{j}^{*},a_{j})\]

Take a look at each of these additional variables against Booked.

Ask Amount

Above 50% close rate at every level, but the poorest close rate is between the $100k to $1M levels. Theres obviously nonlinearity; a cubic polynomial might be a good approximation?

Ask Amount/Planned Amount

I think differences in planned ask versus actual ask amounts might indicate trouble. How does the ratio of actual ask over planned ask look?

Too choppy to really see much of anything; most solicitations are asked at the planned amount and there are so few in the tails that there isnt much interesting to say. What if we just look at a few binned thresholds?

If someone asks slightly more than the planned ask amount its a good sign that the talks were going well; otherwise there doesnt seem to be much to see here. The 25%-50% bin might also be statistically significant; dont know about the others given the small sample sizes.

There are a couple of crossover points; January for Plan and Clear; Jan or Feb for ask (though it crosses back in March interestingly). Cant count on oral pledges made in May or June coming in before the end of the year. Lets restrict the plot to just asks in the MG range, \(x\in[100k,5M)\):

Ha, thats more like it. Plan has a negative trend after Feb; Clear is surprisingly close to flat; Ask has a negative trend after March; Oral cant be counted on in May and June.
